bio: Africa Mincey is an accessibility engineer and occupational therapist with a passion for making websites usable for people of all abilities. As an occupational therapist she helped individuals with acute injuries and disabilities increase independence with rehabilitative exercise and  assistive technology tools. She transitioned away from direct patient care to work as a Web developer building full stack web applications. She now specializes in analyzing and testing software for adherence to the digital accessibility laws covered under the Americans With Disabilities Act.

sessions.name: Intro to Web Accessibility for Web developers and Designers

bio: Highly focused on transforming underserved communities into capital markets, Alaxandria works at the intersection of Community Development; Technology; and Venture Capital. Known as a super-connector and ecosystem builder, Alaxandria spends the majority of her time serving as a conduit for local Black and Brown founders and those interested in entering the Chicago market. Currently, she has her hands busy building online communities such as Goodie Nation and organizing culturally relevant tech opportunities for the South Side via Black Tech Migrants, a subsidiary brand of the ChiTechCLLCT.

sessions.name: Milieu: How higher education can transition underserved communities

bio: Anthony is a data engineer turned software engineer who loves working on backend platforms and nerding out about all things data. Currently working on the Growth Data Engineering team at Netflix, his previous experience includes time as a software engineer in Content Engineering at Netflix, as well as time at Mailchimp, Cerner, and Bank of America to name a few. Anthony holds Computer Science degrees from both the historic Clark Atlanta University, as well as DePaul University, and has further expanded his expertise with Kubernetes, Apache Cassandra, and Google Cloud Data Engineering certifications. Anthony is extremely passionate about mentoring and supporting those from underrepresented communities in tech and is always open to a coffee chat and meeting someone new. You can always find Anthony on various social platforms as @antculver.

bio:
Athena marries neuroscience and spirituality to bring embodied yet practical insight to the stage. She is passionate about showing neurodivergent creators how to develop supportive practices that help them navigate uncertainty with confidence.

You can learn more about Athena at athenasayaka.com !

bio: After a corporate hiatus dedicated to family and acting, Brandi re-entered the business world with a renewed purpose. Co-founder of Juneteenth Conference, she leverages her expertise in customer service, community engagement, and human resources to drive positive change. Brandi's unwavering focus is on Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion (DEI) in and beyond her workplace. She is dedicated to fostering an inclusive society.

When Dolly is not working, the Brooklyn native is likely traveling, gaming, or becoming better versed in beauty, fashion, health, fitness & so much more!

bio: Minda Harts is the bestselling and award-winning author of The Memo: What Women of Color Need to Know to Secure a Seat at the Table as well as Right Within: How to Heal from Racial Trauma in the Workplace, and her first YA book, You Are More Than Magic. She is a highly sought-after speaker and thought-leader, frequently presenting on the topics of advancing women of color, leadership, diversity, and management at companies like Nike, Google, JP Morgan, Aspen Ideas Festival, Dreamforce, The Atlantic Festival, Forbes Inclusion in The Workplace, and DraftKings to name a few. Minda is an assistant professor of public service at NYU's Robert F. Wagner Graduate School of Public Service and the founder of The Memo LLC, a career development company. In 2020, Minda was named by LinkedIn as the #1 Top Voice for Equity in the Workplace. In 2022, She was named by Business Insider as one the the top 100 People Transforming Business. Additionally, Minda was chosen by Marie Claire Magazine in 2022 to participate in Power Trip, where the year‚Äôs Top Women Movers and Shakers participate in an all-expense paid trip to network with each other. She has a weekly career podcast for women of color, titled Secure the Seat.

bio:
Tim‚Äôs tech career spans over 25 years through various sectors. Tim‚Äôs initial journey into tech started in avionics in the US Marine Corps and then into various government contracting roles. After moving to the private sector, Tim worked both in large corporate environments and in small startups, honing his skills in systems administration, automation, architecture, and operations for large cloud-based datastores.

Wesley Faulkner is a first-generation American, public speaker, and podcaster. He is a founding member of the government transparency group Open Austin and a staunch supporter of racial justice, workplace equity, and neurodiversity. His professional experience spans technology from AMD, Atlassian, Dell, IBM, and MongoDB. Wesley co-hosts the developer relations focused podcast Community Pulse and serves on the board for SXSW.
